         <entryFree xml:id="feature_name_here" type="architectural-feature">
            <term xml:id="term-feature_name-4" xml:lang="zh-latn-pinyin" type="preferred">yǐngzuò
               mùgòu</term>
            <term xml:id="term-feature_name-1" xml:lang="en">Painted representation of timber
               architecture</term>
            <term xml:id="term-feature_name-2" xml:lang="zh-Hant" source="#biblk000099-1">影作木構</term>
            <term xml:id="term-feature_name-3" xml:lang="zh-Hans">影作木构</term>
            <term xml:id="term-feature_name-5" xml:lang="Wade-Giles">ying-tso mu-kou</term>
            <term xml:id="term-feature_name-6" xml:lang="en" type="literal_translation">Shadow-works
               timber structure</term>
            <note>
               <p>First coined in the 1980s (Su Bai 1982), yingzuo mugou is a modern term adopted by
                  archaeologists and art historians referring to painted representations of timber
                  architectural components in tombs. The meaning of yingzuo here as a “painted
                  representation of something” has departed from its original context in the Yingzao
                  fashi. Similar appropriations appeared in 1950s (Su Bai 1957), such as in yingzuo
                  men e (painted representations of door lintels in tombs), and yingzuo puzuo
                  (painted representations of corbeling (bracket sets) in tombs).</p>
               <p source="#biblk000099-2">現代考古、美術學界用語，最早出現于1980年代（宿白 1981,
                  142），指墓室之中彩畫繪出的木構建築構件，這裏“影作”的含義與其最初語境（即《營造法式》）有別，相似用法最早見於1950年代，如“影作門額”、“影作鋪作”等</p>
               <p>Related Concepts: <term ref="/keyword/k000100"/>shadow works 影作</p>
